{"title_page": "David Bull (politician)", "text_new": "{{about||the Tokyo-based Canadian printmaker|David Bull (artist)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = David Bull\n| party               = [[Brexit Party|Brexit]] (since 2019)\n| otherparty          = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] (before 2019)\n| image               = File:David Bull - Photo by Jenny Smith 07.jpg\n| caption             = Bull in 2020\n| office              = [[Member of the European Parliament]]<br>for [[North West England (European Parliament constituency)|North West England]]\n| term_start          = [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2 July 2019]]\n| term_end            = 31 January 2020\n| predecessor         = [[Steven Woolfe]]\n| successor           = ''Constituency abolished''\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1969|05|09|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Farnborough, London|Farnborough]], [[London]], England\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| nationality         = British\n| spouse              = \n| relations           = \n| children            = \n| residence           = \n| education           = [[Framlingham College]]\n| alma_mater          = [[Imperial College London]]\n| occupation          = Medical doctor, television presenter, author, politician\n| profession          = \n| website             = [http://www.davidbull.com davidbull.com]\n}}\n'''David Richard Bull''' (born 9 May 1969) is an English medical doctor, television presenter, author and former politician, who was a [[Member of the European Parliament]] (MEP) for [[North West England (European Parliament constituency)|North West England]] from [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2019]] until 2020.\n\nBull has worked in television for over twenty years and has worked for major UK networks including the [[BBC]], [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]], [[Channel 4]] and [[Channel 5 (British TV channel)|Channel 5]], as well as for [[Living TV Group|Living TV]], [[Sky UK|Sky TV]] and [[Food Network#Food Network around the world|Food Network]]. He also works on radio stations including [[BBC Radio 2]], [[BBC Radio 5 Live]], [[Talksport|talkRADIO]] and [[LBC]]. His credits on British and US television programmes include ''[[Jeremy Vine (TV programme)|The Jeremy Vine Show]]'', ''[[Sugar Dome]]'', ''[[Watchdog (TV programme)|Watchdog]]'', ''[[The Alan Titchmarsh Show]]'', ''[[Newsround]]'', ''[[Most Haunted Live!]],'' ''[[Richard & Judy]]'', ''[[Tomorrow's World]]'', and ''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]].'' He has been a panellist on ''[[The Wright Stuff]]'' on Channel 5, and has made appearances on ''[[Rachael Ray (talk show)|The Rachael Ray Show]]'' in the US. He starred in 2013 [[romantic comedy]] film [[Cavemen (film)|''Cavemen'']].\n\nIn 2006, Bull was nominated as the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] candidate for [[Brighton Pavilion (UK Parliament constituency)|Brighton Pavilion]] in the following general election. He stood down in 2009 to head up a Conservative policy review on sexual health, an area about which he has been outspoken, and was replaced by [[Charlotte Vere, Baroness Vere of Norbiton|Charlotte Vere]].\n\nBull was a [[Brexit Party]] [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] for [[North West England (European Parliament constituency)|North West England]], between the [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2019 European Parliament election]] and the [[Brexit|United Kingdom's withdrawal from the EU]] on 31 January 2020.\n\n==Early life==\nDavid Bull was born in [[Farnborough, Kent]], to Richard and Pauline Bull, and moved to [[Framlingham]], [[Suffolk]], at the age of four with his siblings Anthony and Katie. In Suffolk, Bull attended [[Fairfield Preparatory School]] followed by [[Ipswich School|Ipswich Preparatory School]] before graduating to [[Framlingham College]]. At Framlingham, Bull cultivated interests in music and drama, and was made Head of the Day Boys in the Upper Sixth, working to fight [[bullying]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pupiline.net/aboutus/endorsements/000919472031.cfm |title=pipeline.net |access-date=10 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204153555/http://www.pupiline.net/aboutus/endorsements/000919472031.cfm |archive-date=4 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBull went to [[St Mary's Hospital Medical School]] at [[Imperial College London]], graduating with a [[Bachelor of Medicine]] degree, a [[Bachelor of Surgery]] degree (MBBS) and a first class [[Bachelor of Science]] honours degree (BSc) in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://davidbull.com/index.php/about-me/|title=ABOUT ME - David Bull|work=davidbull.com|accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref> He was a [[pre-registration house officer]] at [[St Mary's Hospital, London|St Mary's Hospital]] in [[Paddington]] and worked for the [[National Health Service (England)|NHS]] in the fields of [[Emergency Medicine]] at [[Ealing Hospital NHS Trust]], and General Medicine and Emergency Medicine at [[Whittington Hospital]] in London.<ref name=\"davidbull.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://davidbull.com/index.php/resume-3/ |title=davidbull.com |access-date=3 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321062123/http://davidbull.com/index.php/resume-3/ |archive-date=21 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Medical career==\nDespite having wanted to be a doctor since childhood, Bull described working for the NHS as tough. Nevertheless, he continued to work in general medicine as a [[Pre-registration house officer|house officer]] and [[senior house officer]] in general medicine, surgery and accident and emergency. Frustrated with the lack of knowledge patients had, he felt that no one was concentrating on proactive health, stopping people from becoming ill in the first place, so he took up that challenge. He pursued his interest in broadcasting - specifically television, combining his new role with his ongoing clinical duties.<ref>[http://davidbull.com/index.php/about-me/ About me] DavidBull.com</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=May 2019}} He holds full medical registration with the General Medical Council and had his licence to practise restored in March 2020 in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|spreading]] to the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>[https://www.gmc-uk.org/registration-and-licensing/the-medical-register The Medical Register] General Medical Council</ref>\n\n==Media career==\nIn 1995, Bull auditioned to be a guest commentator for ''The Sky Travel Guide'' on [[Sky Real Lives|Sky Travel]]. Of the auditioning process Bull recalled, \"I had to read autocue, I had to interview someone, and I had to handle a live show...you can't beat that sort of experience.\" Bull was awarded the position on Sky Travel, giving advice for the holiday health feature to those traveling abroad, and beginning his career as a television commentator and presenter.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/schools/studentlife/careersandchoices/dreamjobs/mediaandentertainment/presenter/interview_presenter_david_bull.shtml |title=BBC Online |access-date=14 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100807112655/http://www.bbc.co.uk/schools/studentlife/careersandchoices/dreamjobs/mediaandentertainment/presenter/interview_presenter_david_bull.shtml |archive-date=7 August 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nWithin months of appearing on ''The Sky Travel Guide'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/589033?view=synopsis|title=Tell Me about It! (1996)|publisher=British Film Institute|accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref> Bull joined the long-running ''[[Newsround]]'' as a presenter and producer of segments regarding children's health. Bull's reports on ''Newsround'' were also featured on [[BBC News]], including a documentary on bullying that won the [[Royal Television Society Award]] for Best Children's Factual programme.<ref name=\"davidbull.com\"/>{{Primary source inline|date=May 2019}}\n\nWhilst on ''Newsround'', Bull became a regular on popular kids shows on Saturday mornings for [[CBBC (TV channel)|CBBC]], ''The Weather Show'', ''Saturday Aardvark'', ''K Club'' and ''Bitesize Debate'' specials. He also hosted, in his role as a doctor, ''Why Me?'' and ''Call the Doctor''. Bull then became the sole presenter of ''Tell Me About It!'' for New Zealand's [[C4 (New Zealand TV channel)|C4]] TV station. Aimed at young people, the five-instalment programme tackled issues including eating disorders, parental divorces and teen drug use and alcoholism.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1216005/|title=David Bull|work=IMDb.com|accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Bull published his first book, ''Cool and Celibate?: Sex and No Sex'', arguing the benefits of [[abstinence]] in teenagers, translated in multiple languages. Bull followed his first book with ''What Every Girl Should Know: An A to Z of Health-From Allergies to Zits!'' in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://davidbull.com/index.php/books/|title=BOOKS - David Bull|work=DavidBull.com|accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nBull joined the [[BBC]]'s ''[[Watchdog (TV programme)|Watchdog]]'' in 1999. While on ''Watchdog'', he also appeared on ''Holiday'', ''Let's Get Healthy'', ''The Really Useful Show'', ''Daily Live'' and ''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]''. He then hosted ''Watchdog Healthcheck'', a weekly, half-hour health programme running from 2001 to 2002.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn addition to appearing on ''Healthcheck'', Bull presented the science and technology-centred ''[[Tomorrow's World]]'', before presenting ''[[Most Haunted]]'' on Living TV.<ref name=\":0\" /> Bull appeared on Live TV's highest rated series, ''[[Most Haunted Live!]]'' from October 2002 to October 2005, hosting three-hour instalments that featured [[paranormal]] investigations broadcast live with interactive sections involving the audience. Bull also participated in a [[Ghost hunting|ghost hunt]] at Choughs Hotel where he claimed to have seen an [[apparitional experience|apparition]], though he admitted it could have been an optical illusion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kAeVLWN5VPY|title=Jon Dibley & David Bull|author=Carlie Cliffe|date=27 November 2010|publisher=|accessdate=13 September 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nBull made his American television debut in 2010 as a contributor on the daytime talk show ''[[Rachael Ray (TV series)|The Rachael Ray Show]]''. First appearing on the 12 April 2010 segment \"Why You Crave Food\", Bull discussed the effects of high-fat, high-calorie foods on the brain and gave advice on cutting down on cravings.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rachaelrayshow.com/show/segments/view/im-addicted-food/ |title=Rachael Ray Show |access-date=14 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929005911/http://www.rachaelrayshow.com/show/segments/view/im-addicted-food/ |archive-date=29 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On 23 July 2010, Bull returned to ''The Rachel Ray Show'' to discuss \"Mystery Diseases\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rachaelrayshow.com/show/segments/view/solving-mystery-diseases/ |title=Rachael Ray Show |access-date=14 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929005922/http://www.rachaelrayshow.com/show/segments/view/solving-mystery-diseases/ |archive-date=29 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Bull started hosting for Food Network's series ''[[Sugar Dome]]'' which is broadcast in the US, Canada, Asia and the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foodnetwork.com/sugar-dome/|title=Sugar Dome|work=Food Network|publisher=Scripps Interactive|accessdate=13 September 2018}}{{dead link|date=May 2019}}</ref> He has also co-presented ''Coast vs Country'' on Channel 4.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2013, Bull starred in [[romantic comedy]] film [[Cavemen (film)|''Cavemen'']].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Political career==\nIn December 2006, Bull was selected to represent the Parliamentary seat of [[Brighton Pavilion (UK Parliament constituency)|Brighton Pavilion]] at the 2010 [[United Kingdom general elections|general election]] for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]], after being placed on the party's [[A-List (Conservative)|A-List]] earlier that year. He withdrew his candidacy in June 2009 and was replaced by Charlotte Vere.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/sussex/8367733.stm|title=Tory candidate chosen in primary|date=19 November 2009|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref> Denying rumours that he quit after falling out with party leadership, Bull cited the increased workload accompanying his recent appointment to head up a Conservative policy review on sexual health with Shadow Health Minister [[Anne Milton]].<ref name=ToryFallout>{{cite web|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/4466512.Celebrity_doctor_denies_fall_out_with_Tories|title=Celebrity doctor denies fall-out with Tories|author=Andy Chiles|date=30 June 2009|work=The Argus|accessdate=13 September 2018|publisher=Newsquest Media (Southern)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2009/06/david-bull-steps-down-as-candidate-for-brighton-pavilion-to-head-up-policy-review.html|title=ConservativeHome's Seats & Candidates blog: David Bull steps down as candidate for Brighton Pavilion to head up policy review|author=Jonathan Isaby|date=26 June 2009|work=Conservative Home|accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Bull was announced as a [[Brexit Party]] candidate in the upcoming [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|European Parliament election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.westmonster.com/brexit-party-reveal-another-diverse-group-of-mep-candidates1/|title=Brexit Party reveal another diverse group of MEP candidates|date=25 April 2019|work=Westmonster|accessdate=25 April 2019|author=Westmonster}}</ref> He was duly returned as an MEP for the [[North West England (European Parliament constituency)|North West England]] constituency in the election held on 23 May.<ref>{{cite news |title=Brexit Party wins three North West seats |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-48417394 |accessdate=22 August 2019 |work=BBC News |date=27 May 2019}}</ref> Later, in August of that year, Bull was adopted as the Brexit Party's [[prospective parliamentary candidate]] (PPC) for [[Central Suffolk and North Ipswich (UK Parliament constituency)|Central Suffolk and North Ipswich]] then subsequently [[Sedgefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Sedgefield]] in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/politics/constituencies/E14000915|title=Sedgefield parliamentary constituency|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=2019-12-22|url-status=live|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nBull was among the UK MEPs who stood down following the [[Brexit|UK's withdrawal]] from the [[European Union]] on 31 January 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Barnes|first=Peter|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-46393399|title=What happens after Brexit?|date=5 February 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Business and charitable work==\nIn 2000, Bull founded the creative branding company, Incredibull.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.incredibull.com/|title=Incredibull has moved|work=Incredibull|accessdate=13 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108205904/http://www.incredibull.com/|archive-date=8 November 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> He sold his interest in the business in 2017.\n\nBull is a supporter of The Cystic Fibrosis Trust, (a charity he has been associated with for over twenty years), The British Red Cross, Cancer Research and [[The Duke of Edinburgh's Award]] and has worked with young people in schools on behalf of the organisation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dofe.org|title=The Duke of Edinburgh's Award \u2013 The DofE in the UK|publisher=Duke of Edinburgh Award|accessdate=13 September 2018}}{{Failed verification|date=May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBull is openly [[gay]]. In 2007 he appeared at the [[Brighton Pride]] Parade for which he designed and wore a t-shirt with the slogan \"I've come out... I'm a [[Tory]]\", saying it was acceptable to be gay and a Conservative.<ref name=ToryFallout/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.davidbull.com davidbull.com]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130613011402/http://www.incredibull.com/ incredibull.com]\n\n{{Brexit Party}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bull , David}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ipswich School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Framlingham College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Imperial College London]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) politicians]]\n[[Category:Brexit Party MEPs]]\n[[Category:Brexit Party parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:21st-century English politicians]]\n[[Category:Medical journalists]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English television journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:LGBT broadcasters from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from England]]\n[[Category:People from Kent]]\n[[Category:People from Suffolk]]\n[[Category:People from Farnborough, London]]\n[[Category:Critics of the European Union]]\n[[Category:British Eurosceptics]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 2019\u20132020]]\n[[Category:LGBT MEPs for the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:English political commentators]]\n[[Category:English political journalists]]\n[[Category:British television personalities]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the Tokyo-based Canadian printmaker|David Bull (artist)}}{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox MEP\n| name                = David Bull\n| party               = [[Brexit Party|Brexit]] (since 2019)\n| otherparty          = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] (before 2019)\n| image               = File:David Bull - Photo by Jenny Smith 07.jpg\n| caption             = Bull in 2020\n| office              = [[Member of the European Parliament]]<br>for [[North West England (European Parliament constituency)|North West England]]\n| term_start          = [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2 July 2019]]\n| term_end            = 31 January 2020\n| predecessor         = [[Steven Woolfe]]\n| successor           = ''Constituency abolished''\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1969|05|09|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Farnborough, London|Farnborough]], [[London]], England\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| nationality         = British\n| spouse              = \n| relations           = \n| children            = \n| residence           = \n| education           = [[Framlingham College]]\n| alma_mater          = [[Imperial College London]]\n| occupation          = Medical doctor, television presenter, author, politician\n| profession          = \n| website             = [http://www.davidbull.com davidbull.com]\n}}\n'''David Richard Bull''' (born 9 May 1969) is an English medical doctor, television presenter, author and former politician, who was a [[Member of the European Parliament]] (MEP) for [[North West England (European Parliament constituency)|North West England]] from [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2019]] until 2020.\n\nBull has worked in television for over twenty years and has worked for major UK networks including the [[BBC]], [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]], [[Channel 4]] and [[Channel 5 (British TV channel)|Channel 5]], as well as for [[Living TV Group|Living TV]], [[Sky UK|Sky TV]] and [[Food Network#Food Network around the world|Food Network]]. He also works on radio stations including [[BBC Radio 2]], [[BBC Radio 5 Live]], [[Talksport|talkRADIO]] and [[LBC]]. His credits on British and US television programmes include ''[[Jeremy Vine (TV programme)|The Jeremy Vine Show]]'', ''[[Sugar Dome]]'', ''[[Watchdog (TV programme)|Watchdog]]'', ''[[The Alan Titchmarsh Show]]'', ''[[Newsround]]'', ''[[Most Haunted Live!]],'' ''[[Richard & Judy]]'', ''[[Tomorrow's World]]'', and ''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]].'' He has been a panellist on [[The Wright Stuff|''The Wright Stuff'']] on Channel 5, and has made appearances on ''[[Rachael Ray (talk show)|The Rachael Ray Show]]'' in the US. He starred in 2013 [[romantic comedy]] film [[Cavemen (film)|''Cavemen'']].\n\nIn 2006, Bull was nominated as the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] candidate for [[Brighton Pavilion (UK Parliament constituency)|Brighton Pavilion]] in the following general election. He stood down in 2009 to head up a Conservative policy review on sexual health, an area about which he has been outspoken, and was replaced by [[Charlotte Vere, Baroness Vere of Norbiton|Charlotte Vere]].\n\nBull was a [[Brexit Party]] [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] for [[North West England (European Parliament constituency)|North West England]], between the [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2019 European Parliament election]] and the [[Brexit|United Kingdom's withdrawal from the EU]] on 31 January 2020.\n\n==Early life==\nDavid Bull was born in [[Farnborough, Kent]], to Richard and Pauline Bull, and moved to [[Framlingham]], [[Suffolk]], at the age of four with his siblings Anthony and Katie. In Suffolk, Bull attended [[Fairfield Preparatory School]] followed by [[Ipswich School|Ipswich Preparatory School]] before graduating to [[Framlingham College]]. At Framlingham, Bull cultivated interests in music and drama, and was made Head of the Day Boys in the Upper Sixth, working to fight [[bullying]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pupiline.net/aboutus/endorsements/000919472031.cfm |title=pipeline.net |access-date=10 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204153555/http://www.pupiline.net/aboutus/endorsements/000919472031.cfm |archive-date=4 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBull went to [[St Mary's Hospital Medical School]] at [[Imperial College London]], graduating with a [[Bachelor of Medicine]] degree, a [[Bachelor of Surgery]] degree (MBBS) and a first class [[Bachelor of Science]] honours degree (BSc) in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://davidbull.com/index.php/about-me/|title=ABOUT ME - David Bull|work=davidbull.com|accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref> He was a [[pre-registration house officer]] at [[St Mary's Hospital, London|St Mary's Hospital]] in [[Paddington]] and worked for the [[National Health Service (England)|NHS]] in the fields of [[Emergency Medicine]] at [[Ealing Hospital NHS Trust]], and General Medicine and Emergency Medicine at [[Whittington Hospital]] in London.<ref name=\"davidbull.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://davidbull.com/index.php/resume-3/ |title=davidbull.com |access-date=3 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321062123/http://davidbull.com/index.php/resume-3/ |archive-date=21 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Medical career==\nDespite having wanted to be a doctor since childhood, Bull described working for the NHS as tough. Nevertheless, he continued to work in general medicine as a [[Pre-registration house officer|house officer]] and [[senior house officer]] in general medicine, surgery and accident and emergency. Frustrated with the lack of knowledge patients had, he felt that no one was concentrating on proactive health, stopping people from becoming ill in the first place, so he took up that challenge. He pursued his interest in broadcasting - specifically television, combining his new role with his ongoing clinical duties.<ref>[http://davidbull.com/index.php/about-me/ About me] DavidBull.com</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=May 2019}} He holds full medical registration with the General Medical Council and had his licence to practise restored in March 2020 in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|spreading]] to the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>[https://www.gmc-uk.org/registration-and-licensing/the-medical-register The Medical Register] General Medical Council</ref>\n\n==Media career==\nIn 1995, Bull auditioned to be a guest commentator for ''The Sky Travel Guide'' on [[Sky Real Lives|Sky Travel]]. Of the auditioning process Bull recalled, \"I had to read autocue, I had to interview someone, and I had to handle a live show...you can't beat that sort of experience.\" Bull was awarded the position on Sky Travel, giving advice for the holiday health feature to those traveling abroad, and beginning his career as a television commentator and presenter.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/schools/studentlife/careersandchoices/dreamjobs/mediaandentertainment/presenter/interview_presenter_david_bull.shtml |title=BBC Online |access-date=14 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100807112655/http://www.bbc.co.uk/schools/studentlife/careersandchoices/dreamjobs/mediaandentertainment/presenter/interview_presenter_david_bull.shtml |archive-date=7 August 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nWithin months of appearing on ''The Sky Travel Guide'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/589033?view=synopsis|title=Tell Me about It! (1996)|publisher=British Film Institute|accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref> Bull joined the long-running ''[[Newsround]]'' as a presenter and producer of segments regarding children's health. Bull's reports on ''Newsround'' were also featured on [[BBC News]], including a documentary on bullying that won the [[Royal Television Society Award]] for Best Children's Factual programme.<ref name=\"davidbull.com\"/>{{Primary source inline|date=May 2019}}\n\nWhilst on ''Newsround'', Bull became a regular on popular kids shows on Saturday mornings for [[CBBC (TV channel)|CBBC]], ''The Weather Show'', ''Saturday Aardvark'', ''K Club'' and ''Bitesize Debate'' specials. He also hosted, in his role as a doctor, ''Why Me?'' and ''Call the Doctor''. Bull then became the sole presenter of ''Tell Me About It!'' for New Zealand's [[C4 (New Zealand TV channel)|C4]] TV station. Aimed at young people, the five-instalment programme tackled issues including eating disorders, parental divorces and teen drug use and alcoholism.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1216005/|title=David Bull|work=IMDb.com|accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Bull published his first book, ''Cool and Celibate?: Sex and No Sex'', arguing the benefits of [[abstinence]] in teenagers, translated in multiple languages. Bull followed his first book with ''What Every Girl Should Know: An A to Z of Health-From Allergies to Zits!'' in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://davidbull.com/index.php/books/|title=BOOKS - David Bull|work=DavidBull.com|accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nBull joined the [[BBC]]'s ''[[Watchdog (TV programme)|Watchdog]]'' in 1999. While on ''Watchdog'', he also appeared on ''Holiday'', ''Let's Get Healthy'', ''The Really Useful Show'', ''Daily Live'' and ''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]''. He then hosted ''Watchdog Healthcheck'', a weekly, half-hour health programme running from 2001 to 2002.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn addition to appearing on ''Healthcheck'', Bull presented the science and technology-centred ''[[Tomorrow's World]]'', before presenting ''[[Most Haunted]]'' on Living TV.<ref name=\":0\" /> Bull appeared on Live TV's highest rated series, ''[[Most Haunted Live!]]'' from October 2002 to October 2005, hosting three-hour instalments that featured [[paranormal]] investigations broadcast live with interactive sections involving the audience. Bull also participated in a [[Ghost hunting|ghost hunt]] at Choughs Hotel where he claimed to have seen an [[apparitional experience|apparition]], though he admitted it could have been an optical illusion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kAeVLWN5VPY|title=Jon Dibley & David Bull|author=Carlie Cliffe|date=27 November 2010|publisher=|accessdate=13 September 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nBull made his American television debut in 2010 as a contributor on the daytime talk show ''[[Rachael Ray (TV series)|The Rachael Ray Show]]''. First appearing on the 12 April 2010 segment \"Why You Crave Food\", Bull discussed the effects of high-fat, high-calorie foods on the brain and gave advice on cutting down on cravings.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rachaelrayshow.com/show/segments/view/im-addicted-food/ |title=Rachael Ray Show |access-date=14 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929005911/http://www.rachaelrayshow.com/show/segments/view/im-addicted-food/ |archive-date=29 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On 23 July 2010, Bull returned to ''The Rachel Ray Show'' to discuss \"Mystery Diseases\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rachaelrayshow.com/show/segments/view/solving-mystery-diseases/ |title=Rachael Ray Show |access-date=14 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929005922/http://www.rachaelrayshow.com/show/segments/view/solving-mystery-diseases/ |archive-date=29 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Bull started hosting for Food Network's series ''[[Sugar Dome]]'' which is broadcast in the US, Canada, Asia and the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foodnetwork.com/sugar-dome/|title=Sugar Dome|work=Food Network|publisher=Scripps Interactive|accessdate=13 September 2018}}{{dead link|date=May 2019}}</ref> He has also co-presented ''Coast vs Country'' on Channel 4.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2013, Bull starred in [[romantic comedy]] film [[Cavemen (film)|''Cavemen'']].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Political career==\nIn December 2006, Bull was selected to represent the Parliamentary seat of [[Brighton Pavilion (UK Parliament constituency)|Brighton Pavilion]] at the 2010 [[United Kingdom general elections|general election]] for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]], after being placed on the party's [[A-List (Conservative)|A-List]] earlier that year. He withdrew his candidacy in June 2009 and was replaced by Charlotte Vere.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/sussex/8367733.stm|title=Tory candidate chosen in primary|date=19 November 2009|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref> Denying rumours that he quit after falling out with party leadership, Bull cited the increased workload accompanying his recent appointment to head up a Conservative policy review on sexual health with Shadow Health Minister [[Anne Milton]].<ref name=ToryFallout>{{cite web|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/4466512.Celebrity_doctor_denies_fall_out_with_Tories|title=Celebrity doctor denies fall-out with Tories|author=Andy Chiles|date=30 June 2009|work=The Argus|accessdate=13 September 2018|publisher=Newsquest Media (Southern)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2009/06/david-bull-steps-down-as-candidate-for-brighton-pavilion-to-head-up-policy-review.html|title=ConservativeHome's Seats & Candidates blog: David Bull steps down as candidate for Brighton Pavilion to head up policy review|author=Jonathan Isaby|date=26 June 2009|work=Conservative Home|accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Bull was announced as a [[Brexit Party]] candidate in the upcoming [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|European Parliament election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.westmonster.com/brexit-party-reveal-another-diverse-group-of-mep-candidates1/|title=Brexit Party reveal another diverse group of MEP candidates|date=25 April 2019|work=Westmonster|accessdate=25 April 2019|author=Westmonster}}</ref> He was duly returned as an MEP for the [[North West England (European Parliament constituency)|North West England]] constituency in the election held on 23 May.<ref>{{cite news |title=Brexit Party wins three North West seats |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-48417394 |accessdate=22 August 2019 |work=BBC News |date=27 May 2019}}</ref> Later, in August of that year, Bull was adopted as the Brexit Party's [[prospective parliamentary candidate]] (PPC) for [[Central Suffolk and North Ipswich (UK Parliament constituency)|Central Suffolk and North Ipswich]] then subsequently [[Sedgefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Sedgefield]] in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/politics/constituencies/E14000915|title=Sedgefield parliamentary constituency|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=2019-12-22|url-status=live|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nBull was among the UK MEPs who stood down following the [[Brexit|UK's withdrawal]] from the [[European Union]] on 31 January 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Barnes|first=Peter|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-46393399|title=What happens after Brexit?|date=5 February 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Business and charitable work==\nIn 2000, Bull founded the creative branding company, Incredibull.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.incredibull.com/|title=Incredibull has moved|work=Incredibull|accessdate=13 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108205904/http://www.incredibull.com/|archive-date=8 November 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> He sold his interest in the business in 2017.\n\nBull is a supporter of The Cystic Fibrosis Trust, (a charity he has been associated with for over twenty years), The British Red Cross, Cancer Research and [[The Duke of Edinburgh's Award]] and has worked with young people in schools on behalf of the organisation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dofe.org|title=The Duke of Edinburgh's Award \u2013 The DofE in the UK|publisher=Duke of Edinburgh Award|accessdate=13 September 2018}}{{Failed verification|date=May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBull is openly [[gay]]. In 2007 he appeared at the [[Brighton Pride]] Parade for which he designed and wore a t-shirt with the slogan \"I've come out... I'm a [[Tory]]\", saying it was acceptable to be gay and a Conservative.<ref name=ToryFallout/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.davidbull.com davidbull.com]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130613011402/http://www.incredibull.com/ incredibull.com]\n\n{{Brexit Party}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bull , David}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ipswich School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Framlingham College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Imperial College London]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) politicians]]\n[[Category:Brexit Party MEPs]]\n[[Category:Brexit Party parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:21st-century English politicians]]\n[[Category:Medical journalists]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English television journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:LGBT broadcasters from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from England]]\n[[Category:People from Kent]]\n[[Category:People from Suffolk]]\n[[Category:People from Farnborough, London]]\n[[Category:Critics of the European Union]]\n[[Category:British Eurosceptics]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 2019\u20132020]]\n[[Category:LGBT MEPs for the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:English political commentators]]\n[[Category:English political journalists]]\n[[Category:British television personalities]]\n", "name_user"